<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     08-07 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>10 Die In Indian-Tamil Battle In North, Sinhalese Kill 6 In South</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy fighting between Indian troops
and Tamil rebels claimed 10 lives in northern Sri Lanka on Sunday,
an Indian spokeswoman said.
   In central and southern Sri Lanka, Sinhalese extremists shot and
killed six people over the weekend, according to the Sri Lankan
military command.
   Eight guerrillas and two Indian soldiers died in the clash near
Vavuniya, 135 miles northeast of Colombo, according to a
spokeswoman for the Indian High Commission, or embassy.
   Three Indian soldiers were critically injured, she said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The Sri Lankan command said the victims of Sinhalese attackers
included a Sinhalese army lieutenant who was on home leave in
Kuliyapitiya, 37 miles northeast of Colombo.
   A command spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
army Lt. C.M. Bandara was attacked Sunday by three young Sinhalese
on bicycles.
   Five other people were killed Saturday in the Sinhalese
heartland along the island nation's south coast. Police sources
said all of them were government supporters or were thought to be
police informers.
   About 50,000 Indian soldiers are deployed in Sri Lanka as a
peacekeeping force to try to end the Tamil insurrection against the
Sinhalese-dominated government and enforce a peace plan.
   Sinhalese extremists, who say the plan makes too many
concessions to the minority Tamils, have killed about 400
government officials and supporters since India and Sri Lanka
signed the accord July 29, 1987.
   Sinhalese comprise 75 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people,
while Tamils account for 18 percent. Tamil rebels fighting for a
separate state say their ethnic group is discriminated against in
jobs and education.
</TEXT>
