<DOCNO> AP880807-0012 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-88 1304EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Gulf-Salvage Bjt   08-07 0874</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Salvage, Bjt,0900</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salvage Crews Look Forward To Less Dangerous Work After War</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Iran-Iraq, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRI TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whether they're called
``angels of mercy'' or ``vultures of war,'' the men who have
salvaged hundreds of blasted ships during the Iran-Iraq war say
they won't stop making money if peace breaks out.
   Since attacks on tankers began escalating in 1984, salvage
companies have scrambled for a share of the work once their radios
crackled with calls of ``Mayday, mayday.''
   Despite the danger from air attack, toxic chemicals and flames
so hot that steel ships sometimes melt into the water, salvage
companies persevere because claims on a single tanker can run into
the tens of millions of dollars.
   Large international firms like Smit Tak and Wijsmuller, both
Dutch firms, took the largest share of the work, setting up 24-hour
monitoring stations and fleets of fire-fighting tugs and launches.
   Meanwhile, local entrepreneurs sprang up along the coast from
Dubai's port town of Jebel Ali southeast to the entrance to the
Strait of Hormuz.
   ``Every man and his dog with a boat and a radio listening to
Channel 16 (the international marine emergency frequency) could
become a part-time salvager,'' according to one shipping executive.
   Iran and Iraq are now moving toward a cease-fire in the eight
year war, and if that happens, the work will change. Instead of
rapid response to mayday alerts, the tugs will work on clearing
ship hulks, reconstructing port facilities and dredging neglected
harbors.
   Shipping sources say dozens of dilapidated, war-damaged tankers
and support vessels from Iran's oil fleet may be ready for
demolition as scrap.
   In Dubai, scrap metal merchants bargain fiercely for recycled
steel to sell for industrial use in the Third World. A
supertanker's hull can bring in as much as $20 million.
   Another prime location for salvagers will be the Shatt Al-Arab
dividing Iran and Iraq, which has been closed since the war began.
Lloyd's Shipping Intelligence Unit estimates that as many as 93
cargo vessels and smaller boats are stranded in the shallow estuary
at the northern tip of the Gulf.
   ``The Shatt Al-Arab is a potential gold mine,'' said a surveyor
making plans for a large international company that specializes in
salvaging ships for refitting or resale as scrap.
   Walter Mckenzie, principal surveyor for the Dubai branch of the
Salvage Association, told the Associated Press, ``Once a definite
peace agreement is signed, there should be a dull period of
assessment (of damages) of about six months to a year, and then an
enormous amount of business expansion.''
   During the war, salvagers have been criticized because of the
speed and aggressiveness with which they race to a battered,
burning or sinking ship; the first tug on the spot usually wins the
business.
   But the salvagemen defend their role. ``Hell, yes, I make money,
big money,'' said one who spoke on condition he not be named. ``But
I'm no vulture,'' he added. ``I'm an angel of mercy who just
happens to get paid for saving ships, cargos, and mens' lives.''
   Most shipping sources spoke on condition their names not be
mentioned, just as they have done throughout the tanker war, for
fear of provoking Iraq or Iran into an attack on their vessels or
for fear of compromising their business relations with either party.
   According to Lloyd's, 546 tankers, freighters and small boats
have been caught and damaged or sunk in the tanker war.
   The salvagers make their money from insurers such as Lloyd's of
London; before the salvage tugs go to work, even in the most
dangerous situations, a damaged ship's master must agree to abide
by Lloyd's Open Form, which says that a reasonable fee will be
negotiated if the rescue is successful.
   It can take years to settle payments, which are sometimes
decided under arbitration. Although sometimes no salvage fee is
awarded, the figure can spiral to $50 million for a badly damaged
supertanker.
   Several tugs have been damaged by air attacks, and others have
been damaged or sunk while trying to make good a rescue.
   On January 27, the 740-ton tug Salverve took the 225,668-ton
Cypriot tanker Coral Cape under tow after an Iraqi missile attack
that killed two South Korean seamen. The Iraqis came back, blasting
the Salverve and killing its British captain and his Filipino chief
engineer.
   In another attack, the world's biggest supertanker, the
565,000-ton Seawise Giant, on charter to Iran, was hit by three
Iraqi bombs. To one side, the 235,000-ton Spanish tanker Barcelona,
took two hits. On the other side, the Greek-registered Argosy
escaped the warplanes but was destroyed by fire.
   ``She just cooked in burning oil so hot that she actually melted
down in the water,'' said one source. Eighteen lives were lost in
the attack.
   Salvage tugs gathered around the inferno of tankers and spilling
crude oil. Three days later they were still wetting down the
smoldering hulks when the Barcelona erupted in a secondary
explosion.
   A tug from the Scandanavian salvage company Scan-Act vanished;
the vessel and its nine-man crew were believed to have been sucked
into the Barcelona and incinerated. Three men on a Belgian tug also
died, and three more tugs were destroyed by fire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
