<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Refugees-Africa Bjt   08-07 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Refugees-Africa, Bjt,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Worries About Africa's Refugees; Sends Team to Somalia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials, concerned about hundreds of
thousands of refugees in the war-torn Horn of Africa, are sending a
team to Somalia this week to try to figure out what can be done to
help people.
   Rebel fighting in Somalia on Africa's east coast has caused more
than 200,000 refugees to flee into Ethiopia, moving at the rate of
1,000 a day since heavy fighting erupted last May, officials say.
   Ironically, Ethiopia, one of Africa's poorest countries headed
by a Marxist dictatorship, has been a haven in recent months for
refugees from Somalia to its east and Sudan to the west.
   Still, there are more Ethiopian refugees living in Sudan and
Somalia than Sudanese and Somalis living in Ethiopia.
   ``The whole Horn of Africa is in turmoil,'' said Patricia Fagan,
a spokeswoman for the U.N. High Commission on Refugees.
   When Somali refugees arrive by foot in Ethiopia, there is
nothing for them at the camps run by Ethiopian relief workers,
Fagan said. Water is scarce and shelters have yet to be built, she
said.
   ``The Somali situation for us is confused,'' she said. ``This is
anxious.''
   Complicating the picture is that fighting in northern Somalia is
occurring near the camps where 370,000 Ethiopian refugees live, she
said.
   The U.S. government has dispatched a three-person team to
Somalia to find out more about conditions in the remote northern
part of the pastoral country, according to Bart Kull, a spokesman
for the Agency for International Development.
   ``Because of the war, we are in the dark,'' he said. ``Their
purpose is to try to assess what may be needed in terms of
humanitarian assistance.''
   The fighting, however, may prevent the U.S. team from going near
the northern area, officials said. U.N. officials evacuated their
people from the region in June for safety reasons, Fagan said.
   The 7-year-old civil war is being waged by the Somali National
Movement, which is seeking to oust Maj. Gen. Mohammed Siad Barre,
the government leader. Amnesty International, the British-based
human rights organization, recently asked Siad Barre to investigate
``unlawful killings'' in northern Somalia.
   The U.N. has put out an emergency appeal for $11 million to help
the Somali refugees in Ethiopia, but U.S. officials say they have
little extra money for them.
   As worrisome as the Somali situation are recent developments in
southern Sudan where rebels are battling the government. The result
is that 300,000 Sudanese, many weakened by starvation, have walked
to Ethiopia to four refugee camps.
   ``Most of the people arrive in awful, awful shape,'' Fagan said.
They go to the camps where water is scarce and food is limited
because ``even so, they have a chance of being fed.'' The Ethiopian
government refuses to allow U.N. officials or foreign aid workers
to stay in the camps.
   Roger Winter of the U.S. Committee for Refugees, a private
group, recently visited southern Sudan where he said he saw
starving people, hospitals without electricity or antibiotics and
plagues affecting cattle.
   Altogether, nearly a million Sudanese have been displaced as a
result of civil strife in the south.
   ``Policies pursued by the governments of Ethiopia and the Sudan
pose a greater threat to large numbers of their people than does
the renewed drought,'' Rep. Mickey Leland, D-Texas, said last month
at a congressional hearing on the food situation in the two
countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
