<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon-Hostages     08-07 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Hostages,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paper Says Hostages Held in Three Syrian-Policed Areas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Beirut newspaper said Sunday that
Western hostages in Lebanon were held in three locations, including
the Iranian Embassy, under the control of an Iranian official.
   The Ad-Diyar newspaper also said there was a ``certain
flexibility'' regarding the release of British hostages, while the
fate of the other missing foreigners was linked to the developments
in the Persian Gulf war.
   But the Ad-Diyar report also said Iran still was insisting on
the release of 17 pro-Iranian activists held in Kuwait for bombing
the U.S. and French embassies there Dec. 3, 1983.
   Ad-Diyar, which is based in Christian east Beirut, started
publishing just four months ago. Its report was attributed to an
unidentified Syrian security source, and it could not be confirmed.
   Syrian and Lebanese security officials have long contended that
most of the 18 Western hostages in Lebanon were held in the main
barracks of Hezbollah, or Party of God, in Hay Madi distrtict in
south Beirut's slums.
   ``The foreign hostages in Lebanon are divided into three groups
and held in three different locations,'' Ad-Diyar said. It said the
three groups were in the Hezbollah barracks, the Iranian Embassy
and in the Sheik Abdullah barracks in Baalbek, a town in Lebanon's
east Bekaa Valley.
   It said Anglican Church envoy Terry Waite was among the group
held in Baalbek. Waite disappeared Jan. 20, 1987 after leaving his
west Beirut hotel on a mission to negotiate the hostages' release.
   No other names or nationalities of hostages were mentioned in
the report.
   The Iranian-backed Hezbollah is believed to an umbrella group
for various pro-Iranian extremist factions holding hostages.
   The three locations listed are policed by Syrian forces. Syria
has 40,000 troops in eastern and northern Lebanon as well as in
west Beirut and its southern suburbs.
   Ad-Diyar said the hostages ``are controlled by a Hezbollah wing
which answers directly to Tehran.''
   Iran's deputy foreign minister, Hossein Sheikholeslam, was in
Beirut when Syria sent an estimated 2,500 troops into the southern
slums to quell three weeks of bloody fighting between Hezbollah and
the rival Syrian-backed Shiite Moslem Amal militia in May.
   Ad-Diyar said Sheikholeslam managed to smuggle some of the
hostages from Hay Madi to Baalbek and to the Iranian Embassy in
another part of south Beirut before the Syrians moved in. It did
not elaborate on Sheikholeslam's alleged role.
   ``There is a certain flexibility regarding the release of the
British hostages after relations improved between Iran and
Britain,'' Ad-Diyar said.
   ``But the fate of the other hostages will remain closely linked
to the developments in the U.N. Security Council concerning the
Iran-Iraq war,'' the daily added.
   Britain said early this month it was reviewing its strained
relations with Iran following the latter's acceptance of Security
Council Resolution 598, which calls for a cease-fire in the
8-year-old Persian Gulf war.
   Nine Americans are among the 18 Westerners missing in Lebanon.
The longest held is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent
for The Associated Press. He was kidnapped on March 16, 1985 in
Moslem west Beirut.
</TEXT>
