<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Explosion     08-07 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Explosion,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Residents Return Home After Accident, Gas Leak</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELSBERRY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A defective wheel bearing was the apparent
cause of a freight train derailment that started a nine-hour fire,
released a cloud of hazardous gas and displaced 600 residents, a
railroad official said Sunday.
   A preliminary investigation showed that the bearing apparently
burned off a wheel of one of the train's 113 cars, causing 14 cars
to derail and hit chemical and fuel tanks Saturday, said Brian
Sweeney, a spokesman for Burlington Northern Railroad.
   Missouri Highway 79 was re-opened for traffic Sunday morning,
except for the area immediately surrounding the crash site, said
Rob Brown, public relations officer for the Boone County Fire
District.
   People who were forced to spend the night in a church and school
near this eastern Missouri town were allowed back into their homes
at about 11 a.m. Sunday, after workers had removed anhyrdous
ammonia from a leaking tank.
   The evacuation was ordered after several rail cars caught fire
when they derailed at about 6 a.m. en route from Galesburg, Ill.,
to St. Louis.
   The fire took more than nine hours to contain, but firefighters
kept the blaze from igniting nearly 28,000 gallons of diesel,
kerosene and gasoline being stored nearby.
   Residents were not allowed to return home after the fire was
extinguished, because anhydrous ammonia was leaking from a
punctured tank. The ammonia is dangerous to respiratory systems and
can cause severe burns, said Troy Fire Chief Gerald Cherry.
   Several firefighters suffered minor injuries fighting the blaze,
but no injuries were reported by residents or the train's crew.
   Ronnie Herrin, 49, a train buff who witnessed the accident, said
he heard the sound of metal crashing and banging.
   ``I knew what it was,'' he said. ``You know how people say when
a tornado goes through that it sounded like a freight train? Well,
this sounded like a tornado.''
</TEXT>
