<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SpaceShuttle     08-07 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Shuttle,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shuttle Engineers Exchange Defective Valve Assembly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mechanics reconnected pipes and
electrical lines on the space shuttle Discovery on Sunday after
exchanging a part that caused a computer to scrub a crucial
test-firing of the shuttle's main engines.
   The one-inch hydrogen bleed valve, and the sensor that reports
its open or closed position, were removed and replaced Saturday
inside the shuttle's cramped engine compartment.
   ``Everything is going perfectly so far,'' said Lisa Mallone,
spokeswoman for NASA's Kennedy Space Center.
   ``We might set a new date for the test-firing tomorrow, if
everything continues to go well.''
   Still ahead were the tasks of checking the reconnected lines for
leaks, and electrical checks on the engine system, including the
new valve.
   The valve, which must be closed during engine firing, was
reported by the faulty sensor to be partially open Thursday, and
computers stopped the hot-fire test.
   A successful test is required before the shuttle can be launched
on America's first manned mission since the Challenger disaster in
1986. No launch date has been set but a launch appears to be
impossible until at least early October.
</TEXT>
