<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Zoo-Orangutans     08-07 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zoo-Orangutans,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zoo Atlanta's Newest Habitat Allows Orangutans To Climb To New
Heights</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-New Zoos, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM E. SCHULZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The once-maligned Zoo Atlanta has built a new
home for its orangutans that gives the natural hambones room to
show off and feel more at home than they would in a cage.
   The key is that the new half-acre ``Orangutans of Ketambe''
exhibit, which opened to the public Saturday, provides a place for
the endangered red apes to climb as they do in the rain forests of
their native Borneo or Sumatra.
   ``When they are kept in a cage that doesn't have good climbing
opportunities, they stay on the floor, and look like a big, red
rug,'' said Zoo Director Terry Maple. ``The way to see a male
orangutan is when he stretches out, hanging by one hand from some
material that looks like a tree.''
   The habitat has two tall trees, other structures for climbing
and ropes that look like vines, enabling the primates to climb as
high as 40 feet.
   ``Very few zoos have built a habitat that was correct for this
animal. We spent more money on the gorillas than we have on the
orangutans, but I think we've built an innovative habitat,'' said
Maple, a primate behavior specialist who helped build the zoo's
reputation for orangutan breeding and research.
   The orangutan habitat is the latest stage in a $26 million
renovation of the 99-year-old zoo, which just four years ago was
rated by the U.S. Humane Society as one of the nation's worst zoos.
   At that time, some star animals died, and the U.S. Department of
Agriculture slapped sanctions on the zoo for poor animal-care
record-keeping.
   Despite the zoo's problems, ``We've had a very consistent and
remarkable record of breeding orangutans,'' Maple said. ``These
animals have been cared for all these years by Dr. Brent Swenson
and his associates at the primate center.
   Maple said moving the orangutans outdoors is a natural step for
the zoo.
   ``Once they learn to live outdoors, we expect them to be
climbing, positioning themselves high above the public. We think
that's how they should be seen,'' Maple said. ``It will be a
gradual process as they start behaving like orangutans again, since
they haven't had a chance to climb very much in captivity.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
