<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Stalin     08-07 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Stalin,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Writer Calls For Removing Stalin's Body From Kremlin Wall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Josef Stalin's body should be removed from its
place of honor at the Kremlin wall because of the crimes he
committed during his nearly three decades of rule, a writer said in
an article published Sunday.
   ``The fact that the main criminal `of all times and peoples' to
this time rests at the Kremlin wall next to (Lenin's) mausoleum _
isn't this an outrage?'' wrote Alexander Veinshtein, director of
cultural affairs for a Moscow factory that produces electrical
equipment.
   His article in the latest weekly edition of the magazine Ogonyok
refers to the praise the dictator received in the Soviet Union
during his lifetime as the ``greatest leader of all times and all
peoples.''
   Veinshtein's biting criticism is unusual even for today's Soviet
media, which is exposing the repressions under Stalin in which
millions of people died. It was the first public proposal to move
Stalin's remains from the Kremlin wall, the highest place of honor
for Soviet heroes.
   The body of Vladimir Lenin, who led the 1917 revolution, is also
preserved in a mausoleum at the Kremlin wall.
   Ogonyok said it is planning an exhibition of proposals for a
monument to Stalin's victims in October and November at the House
of Culture that Veinshtein directs.
   An unofficial group collected about 30,000 signatures this year
demanding that officials approve construction of such a monument in
Moscow. Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev expressed his support in
early July.
   Ogonyok said it also is planning a week of films, plays and
photography dealing with Stalinism.
</TEXT>
