<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-88 1558EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iran-Iraq-Reax     08-07 0688</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Iraq-Reax,0707</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>with AM-Iran-Iraq, Bjt
^Iranians Calm, Satisfied as Peace Appears Near</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sandbags in front of buildings were still
there. So were the windows with tape across them to prevent
shattering in a missile explosion, and the yellow signs showing the
way to the nearest air-raid shelter.
   But most residents of Tehran, a city of 8 million, seemed
convinced Sunday that these remnants from the last Iraqi missile
attacks in April will disappear before long.
   In New York, Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati said his
government accepted an Iraqi offer for direct peace talks following
a cease-fire in the 8-year-old war. U.N. Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar said a truce could take effect within two weeks.
   There were no sensational headlines in Iran's afternoon
newspapers, which came out before the developments in New York but
after Tehran radio announced Iraq's offer.
   ``New Developments in U.N. Talks for Cease-Fire'' said the small
headline in the Ettela'at newspaper, announcing that Baghdad had
dropped its demand for face-to-face talks before a cease-fire.
   ``Iraqi Regime Under Pressure of World Public Opinion Has
Accepted Cease-Fire,'' read the headline in Kayhan, the other main
afternoon paper.
   Iranians in the street did not seem surprised by news of the
developments, which broke an impasse in U.N. negotiations between
the two belligerents. There were few signs of exuberance.
   ``People were sure the end would come sooner or later,'' said
Said, a middle-aged, English-speaking businessman. ``Iranians know
very well what's going on in the world, perhaps better than many
Westerners.''
   ``Sure, I am happy this will be over at last,'' said Hussein, a
young employee of a well-stocked children's shoe shop who spoke
only broken English. Eiradj, who introduced himself as a former air
force officer, said: ``It is a good thing, it is the end.''
   Speaking only a smattering of English, Eiradj explained he had
tried to obtain political asylum in West Germany in 1985 but had
been refused. His gesturing seemed to indicate he would not try
again.
   ``What did the Iraqis want in direct talks?'' asked Yussuf, an
Iranian businessman. He arrived the night before, his first visit
home since he left to study in the United States before the Islamic
revolution that brought the Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini into power
in 1979.
   ``Do they (Iraq) want to tell us that they started the war, they
were the first to attack the tankers, and they used chemical arms
against our people?'' Yussuf asked.
   Rumors circulated here that the sharp fall of the dollar on the
black market had prompted several suicides or attempted suicides.
   Several exchange dealers, according to the rumors, had jumped to
their deaths from a high-rise building in Ferdovzi Street, said to
be a center of foreign exchage trading.
   The Iranian riyal rose sharply against the dollar and other
currencies because of increased demands for Iranian currency in
hopes of a post-war boom in the Iranian economy.
   The dealers had hoarded dollars in the belief that their value
would continue to rise against the U.S. currency. When the reverse
happened in the past few weeks, they lost their speculative profits.
   The dollar was unofficially quoted at 300 riyals at noon Sunday.
This compared to 785 on Aug.1, and 1,480 before Iran accepted a
cease-fire resolution 598 on July 20.
   The driver of a vintage Chevrolet said he bought his well-kept
car second- hand eight years ago for 3.5 million rials and two
months ago, he was offerered 10 million for it.
   ``Now the price is back where it was in 1981,'' he said with a
grin. ``That means the war is over.''
   Iraq's neighbors in the Persian Gulf praised Baghdad leadership
for agreeing to defer direct talks with Iran until after a
cease-fire, paving the way for a truce.
   Bahrain's Crown Prince Sheik Hamad Bin Isa Al Khalifa said the
move ``will be of benefit and stability for the nations of the
region.''
   In Kuwait, the country closest to the warfront, an official
spokesman said the country's Cabinet ``expressed profound interest
in the ... turn of the Iraq-Iran war to peace.''
</TEXT>
