<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Turks     08-07 0688</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Turks,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Turks Anxious About Dukakis Presidency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An long feud between Turkey and Greece could
hurt the presidential campaign of Michael Dukakis, with
Turkish-Americans worried about how the son of Greek immigrants
would repay some political debts if elected.
   Vastly outweighed by the numbers and resources of
Greek-Americans, Turkish-Americans are feeling as embattled as they
did when Congress imposed an arms embargo on Turkey in 1975 to
punish it for invading the predominantly Greek island of Cyprus.
   Their fears are compounded by the surge of political activity in
the Greek-American community, whose estimated 1 million members
have been galvanized by the prospect of having one of their own run
the White House.
   Prominent Turkish-Americans concede Dukakis would probably do
what's best for the country as a whole. But they say his
indebtedness for the massive support of the Greek-American
community may cause him to appoint some of those supporters to key
posts.
   ``My feeling is that Dukakis is an honorable man,'' said Ayhan
Hakimoglu, chairman of Aydin Corporation in Horsham, Pa., which
manufactures high-technology defense and telecommunications
products. But Dukakis was helped by massive contributions from the
Greek-American community, ``and they'll make demands on him. He'll
be under pressure,'' said Hakimoglu.
   Greek-Americans account for between 15 percent and 25 percent of
Dukakis' campaign contributions.
   With his family and friends, Hakimoglu said, he raised more than
$100,000 for Bush. But he stressed that his support of the
Republican candidate is motivated not only by Turkish
considerations but also by his free-market economic policies.
   Turkish-Americans have felt secure with the Reagan
administration, which has consistently stressed Turkey's importance
as NATO's second-largest military force and its strategic location
as a buffer between the Soviet Union and Europe.
   The United States gives Turkey $10 for every seven it gives
Greece, also a NATO ally but with a smaller military force and more
robust economy.
   Turkish American leaders point to Sen. Paul Sarbanes, a college
friend of Dukakis' and one of the architects of the 1975 embargo
against Turkey, as a potential enemy if Dukakis gets to the White
House.
   Whether he gets an administration job or remains on Capitol
Hill, leaders of the Turkish-American community are concerned the
Greek-American lawmaker would influence Dukakis into adopting
anti-Turkish stands.
   Erol Ozdemir, who runs the only Turkish-American political
action committee in the United States, says he hopes to raise
$400,000 in this election cycle for campaign contributions and
voter registration drives. In 1986 his group _ the Assembly of
Turkish American Associations _ raised $75,000.
   ``Most Turkish-Americans will support Bush because he believes
in a strong NATO and because they're concerned that Dukakis would
interfere with Turkish-American relations,'' said Ozdemir, a
certified public accountant whose father came from Turkey.
   One of the issues at the heart of the Turkish lobby's drive
since its inception in 1985 has been an attempt to defeat a
resolution condemning Turkey for the massacre of nearly 2 million
Armenians between 1915 and 1923. Under pressure from the Reagan
administration and the Turkish lobby, the resolution was narrowly
defeated three times.
   Dukakis has promised to support such a resolution. In a letter
to the Armenian community, Dukakis said the rights of Armenians and
the human rights abuse they suffer in Turkey and elsewhere
``cannot, and must not, be ignored or compromised for reasons of
political expediency.''
   Turkish-Americans are also worried about Dukakis' policies
toward Cyprus. They are concerned he would call for the withdrawal
of all Turkish forces from the island even before a peace
settlement between feuding Turks and Greeks on Cyprus is worked out.
   The question of Cyprus, long dormant, could become relevant for
the next U.S. administration because the two sides have agreed to
hold talks under the auspices of the United Nations.
   Turkey itself has stayed out of the ferment in the
Turkish-American community, unwilling to involve itself in internal
American politics.
   ``All we can hope is that Dukakis will be an even-handed
president, a president of all Americans, not just of the Greeks,''
said Daryal Batibay, the no. 2 diplomat at the Turkish Embassy.
</TEXT>
