<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Earthquake     08-07 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Earthquake,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>At Least 29 Feared Dead After Earthquakes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A series of earthquakes rocked India and
nearby countries, churning up big waves in a Bangladesh river that
capsized three boats and left at least 26 people missing and feared
drowned, officials and news reports said Sunday.
   They said three people died in India during one of the series of
temblors Saturday that also rocked parts of Burma, Nepal, Pakistan
and Afghanistan.
   The quakes injured 50 people in Dhaka, the capital of
Bangladesh, news reports said.
   Pakistani and Nepalese officials said no deaths were reported in
their countries. There was no immediate reports of injuries from
Burma and Afghanistan.
   The Press Trust of India reported that northeastern Assam state
was one of the areas hardest-hit by an earthquake whose epicenter
was close to the India-Burma border. The quake measured 7.3 on the
Richter scale.
   The ews agency said two people were killed and 12 injured when
buildings collapsed in Assam. The third person died in a traffic
accident blamed on the quake.
   The tremors cracked walls, caused other property damage and
triggered landslides in areas of Assam and neighboring Manipur
state.
   In Bangladesh, three boats carrying nearly 200 people capsized
Saturday when another quake churned up big waves in the Jamuna
River near Manikganj, 40 miles west of Dhaka, police said.
   Most passengers swam to safety, according to police in
Manikganj, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Only two bodies were recovered by Sunday afternoon but more than
two dozen people were missing and feared dead, the police said.
   Seismologists in Dhaka measured that quake at 5.2 on the Richter
scale.
   Among the 50 people injured by the tremors in Dhaka were six
students who fractured their legs when they jumped from
second-story windows in their dormitories at Dhaka University, news
reports said.
   A tremor with a Richter scale reading of 6.3 rocked parts of
Pakistan and Nepal Saturday, officials reported. Its epicenter was
in the Hindu Kush mountains of Afghanistan and northern Pakistan.
   The open-ended Richter scale is a gauge of energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by ground movement recorded on a
seismograph.
   A quake with a magnitude of 5 can cause considerable damage, one
of 6 can cause severe damage, and one of 7 is capable of
widespread, heavy damage.
  
</TEXT>
