<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JailEscape     08-07 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jail Escape,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Search Continues For Three Of Five Jail Escapees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS LUNAS, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police searched Sunday for three inmates
described as armed and dangerous who were among five men who
escaped from a county jail by punching a hole in a concrete roof
with a 5-pound chunk of steel plate.
   Two escapees from the Valencia County Jail were recaptured
without incident Saturday while walking along a road.
   Officers raided a house in Belen, near Los Lunas and about 30
miles south of Albuquerque, late Saturday where the three escapees,
all Mexican nationals, were believed to have been hiding, Sheriff
Lawrence Romero said.
   The three apparently had fled minutes earlier and were believed
headed for Mexico, Romero said. A state police roadblock set up on
Interstate 25 near Socorro was taken down early Sunday.
   Romero said police had reason to believe the escapees stole a
pickup that contained a .30-30-caliber rifle, a .22-caliber pistol
and a .22-caliber semi-automatic rifle.
   The five inmates got out early Saturday by using a piece of
steel to chisel a hole through a 4-inch-thick roof, Romero said.
The steel piece was about 2 feet long, 4 inches wide and
three-quarters of an inch thick.
   ``It's pretty rotten concrete, so it probably wasn't too hard to
chisel through,'' said acting chief jailer Larry Askew.
   The hole was made in the roof of a small room housing water
pipes and valves next to the cellblock showers, he said. Inmates
have access to the pipe room to turn on the showers, and the room
is secured with a small iron door.
   Askew said it probably took several days to cut the hole, and
that guards did not routinely check the pipe room. Noise of the
digging could be covered by radios and televisions, he said.
   The escape was reported to the sheriff's department at 8:45
a.m., but probably took place at about 2:30 a.m., Romero said.
   The escapees apparently were being held in one cell, he said.
Hourly bed checks were made but the escapees apparently fooled
guards by putting rolled-up blankets in their beds to make it look
like someone was there, Askew said.
   ``How can you tell me they made their checks and not know
they're missing?'' Romero said. ``Are they saying they're making
their checks but not very well?''
   Arrested Saturday in southern Albuquerque were Damien Gonzales,
21, of Los Lunas, and Tommy Cordova, 19, of Albuquerque, said
sheriff's detective Mark Esparsen.
   A search continued Sunday for Eleno Avila, 24, Cruz Pacheco, 24,
and Jesus Campana, 24, all of Mexico.
   Romero said Avila was being held on charges of aggravated
assault with a motor vehicle, reckless driving and eluding a police
officer; Gonzales was being held on charges of aggravated assault,
battery and criminal damage to property; Cordova was being held on
charges of residential burglary and contributing to the delinquency
of a minor; and Pacheco and Campana were federal prisoners.
   Romero said he did not have the charges against Pacheco and
Campana.
</TEXT>
