<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Solidarity     08-07 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Solidarity,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Solidarity Calls For Nationwide Observance Of Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the banned Solidarity trade
union federation on Sunday urged Polish factory workers to
celebrate the eighth anniversary of the organization.
   The union's National Executive Commission said in a statement
that the Aug. 31 anniversary ``should become an occasion for
remembering workers' rights.''
   It said deteriorating conditions in the workplace and declining
morale over economic recovery justified increased demands for
change.
   ``Growing tension over the last weeks in the coal and copper
mining industries prove that forgetting about social accords ...
inevitably creates conflicts,'' the statement said, referring to
workers in the Rudna copper mine in northern Silesia, who have
accused management of ignoring worker safety.
   The miners gave officials until Aug. 15 to improve working
conditions and threatened to stage a series of protest actions if
their demands aren't met.
   The Solidarity statement called on workers to draw up lists of
wage and safety demands and to press for the restoration of the
group's legal status.
   Solidarity was banned in 1981 after martial law was declared.
   The government accused Solidarity of engaging in anti-government
activity.
   Solidarity's main demand is that the state recognize trade union
pluralism, saying that official government unions do not adequately
represent workers' interests.
   Solidarity has encouraged factory workers to apply for legal
recognition. So far, courts have denied all of the more than two
dozen requests.
   In the port city of Gdansk, hundreds of Solidarity supporters
Sunday held a peaceful rally, an opposition spokesman said.
   The crowd assembled at St. Brygida's church, a Solidarity
gathering point several blocks from the Lenin shipyard, the
spokesman said. The shipyard, where the union was born in August
1980, was in May the center of an eight-day Solidarity-sponsored
strike.
   The demonstrators waved banners and shouted ``Solidarity!'' as
they marched toward the city's train station, said the opposition
spokesman, who refused to give his name. He said police watched but
did not intervene.
</TEXT>
