<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Survivors     08-07 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Survivors,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 300 Found Alive After Floods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers have found 311 people who were missing
and presumed dead after flash floods and heavy rains ravaged a
province on the Chinese coast, a newspaper reported.
   A total of 264 people were confirmed dead and 50 were still
missing from floods that hit Zhejiang province July 29-30, the
Xinmin Evening News said Saturday.
   It did not say how or where the 311 survivors were found.
   The floods came after about 18 inches of rain fell within six
hours in parts of five counties near Ningbo, a city on the East
China Sea, according to Qiu Weikang, a Ningbo city official.
   The Evening News said the rains and flooding destroyed 27,000
houses and 944 schools. More than 52,000 people were moved to
temporary shelters.
   The report said 40 million acres were flooded.
   The economic loss was estimated at more than $162 million, the
paper said, and residents say it was the worst rainfall in the area
in 100 years.
   On Saturday, floods inundated Fenyang county in northern Shanxi
province. The official Xinhua News Agency reported that at least 21
people died and 19 were missing after rain fell for more than three
hours.
   More than 800 people have died in floods this year in coastal,
southern and northern China. Another 500 were killed by a heat wave
in cities in the Yangtze River valley.
</TEXT>
