<1ST_LINE>u a AM-FatalFeud 1stLd-Writethru a0458 08-07 0706</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fatal Feud, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0458,0726</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Search For Answers in Family Battle That Kills Three</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites throughout to raise reference background of feud,
comments by widow on background and events of gun battle, arrested
woman free on bail; No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND RIDGE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A feud between two families that boiled
over into a gun battle, killing three brothers and wounding three
other people, apparently began over car lights shining into one of
their homes, police said.
   The Saturday shootout across a dirt road between the Collins and
Johnson families involved about 15 people on the Johnson side
against four Collins brothers and their wives, said Diana Collins,
widow of one of those killed.
   Ramone Salinas, a friend of the Collins family, was charged with
resisting arrest, but no other charges had been filed by Sunday in
the gunfight, which took place in a rural area near this Florida
Panhandle community. She was freed on bond.
   ``We're just trying to put the facts together at this time to
determine what was homicide and what was self-defense,'' said Capt.
John Dennis, chief of the investigative unit of the Jackson County
sheriff's department.
   Police met Sunday afternoon to discuss the investigation.
``We're still involved in the investigation and there is nothing
else we can release at this time,'' Dennis said.
   Rifles, shotguns and pistols were used in the gun battle, Dennis
said, but he refused to give further details.
   The Johnson family has lived in the farming area for many years,
and the Collins family moved in across the road two years ago. The
Collinses live in three trailers, the Johnsons in a house.
   Marsha Collins, widow of one of the slain brothers, said outside
her home Sunday that the three dead men left behind a total of 15
children under the age of 12, and demanded action against the
Johnsons.
   ``There will be a battle, but it will be in court,'' Mrs.
Collins said. ``We won't stop until they are in jail.''
   There was no comment from the Johnsons, who had left their home
Sunday.
   Sheriff Johnny McDaniel blamed the feud in part on lights from
the Collinses' vehicles shining into the Johnson home as they drove
out at night.
   ``When they complained, they (the Collinses) got so that they
would sit and just shine their lights into the house,'' McDaniel
said.
   Another dispute began when social workers were notified that
some of the Collins children were living in a 42-foot
tractor-trailer parked on the Collins property, the sheriff said.
``They blamed the Johnsons with (reporting) it,'' he said.
   The incident that sparked the shooting, Marsha Collins said,
began Friday night when her husband was testing the motor of a
truck he had fixed, and the Johnsons called police to complain
about the noise.
   Deputies separated the families and sent them back to their
homes, Dennis said.
   Marsha Collins claimed that when the deputies left, the
Johnsons' aimed spotlights in the Collins' windows. The Collins
brothers then went to the street and were confronted by the
Johnsons, she said.
   The Collins brothers only got off one or two shots, she said.
   ``If it wasn't a setup, I don't know what is,'' Marsha Collins
said.
   Marsha Collins blamed a Johnson who she said lives with a niece
of the Collins brothers for starting the shooting.
   Around 2:15 a.m. Saturday, the sheriff's department received a
second call from the Johnson family, Dennis said.
   ``We got troubles,'' the caller told the dispatcher.
   Deputy Mike Lanier said that although the Johnsons are black and
the Collinses are white, he didn't believe the gunfight was
racially motivated.
   ``We've talked with all of them and both families said there was
no racial problem,'' said Dennis.
   Marsha Collins agreed: ``This is not racial. We have no problems
with black people.''
   Deputies answering the second call found Madison Collins, 32,
Marsha Collins' husband, and Herman Collins, 34, dead in the road.
A third brother, Lawrence Collins, 36, died while being taken to
Jackson County Hospital, authorities said. All three were truckers.
   Laughton Collins, 44, Carolyn Collins, 36, and Robert Johnson
Jr., 32, were wounded, officials said. They were listed in stable
condition Sunday.
</TEXT>
