<1ST_LINE>u i AM-India-Capsize 1stLd-Writethru a0422 08-07 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Capsize, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0422,0598</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 400 Hindu Pilgrims Missing In Ganges</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with conflicting reports on cause, number of
passengers, relatives' vigil and changes throughout. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PATNA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials said Sunday they had given up hope
of finding survivors among more than 400 Hindu pilgrims missing
after an overcrowded ferry capsized in the rain-swollen Ganges
River.
   Authorities said there were 100 known survivors from the
Saturday accident. They said 12 bodies had been recovered. But news
reports said Saturday that 38 had been found.
   Officials said the actual death toll may never be known.
   The ferry, carrying more than 500 passengers, capsized at 10:30
a.m. near Katihar, about 650 miles east of New Delhi and 180 miles
from Patna, the capital of Bihar province.
   There were conflicting reports on the cause of the disaster.
First reports said the steam-powered vessel rammed a sand bar while
attempting a curve in the churning river. It overturned about 100
yards from shore and the survivors swam to safety, said Katihar
police inspector N. Kunar.
   State-run Indian television said the two-deck ferry also carried
several vehicles and about 150 bags of wheat, and survivors said
they had protested when the wheat was brought aboard the already
overloaded vessel.
   Soon after leaving the jetty the ferry began to tilt and then
capsized, according to the television report.
   Passengers on the upper deck were tossed into the fast-moving
water, while those on the lower deck were trapped inside, Kunar
said.
   About 100 people gathered on the jetty Sunday and along the
marshy river banks in hopes the bodies of relatives and friends
would be recovered.
   Mangan Chand, whose father and an uncle were on the ferry, said,
``I know they're dead. I am waiting for their bodies so that I can
cremate them.''
   There was more rain Sunday, raising the level of the river.
   ``You can't rescue a body in the river at this time of year
because of the strong current,'' said Mubarak Hussain, a member of
the state legislature.
   ``The ferry is always overcrowded because people have no other
way to cross the river,'' he said. The nearest bridge is about 65
miles away.
   Navy divers were sent from New Delhi and residents near the
river used their boats to help in the search effort, he said.
   Mangan Insane, another member of the legislature, said 565
people had purchased tickets for the 10-minute ride across the
river. Hussain said the ferry could safely carry about 250 people.
   Kerosene lanterns gleamed through the night as relatives of the
victims maintained their vigil. Vendors sold tea to the crowd that
included a few jetty workers and junior government officials.
   The jetty workers said the ferry had a crew of 15-20 men. They
said several policemen, who do not need tickets to ride the ferry,
also were aboard the vessel.
   They said the ferry often was overcrowded, and fights broke out
among passengers if the ferry's operators tried to limit the number
of people going aboard.
   Most of the passengers were Hindu pilgrims crossing the Ganges
to catch a train to Deoghar, where the Hindu shrines are visited by
thousands of pilgrims every day.
   The pilgrims were to carry huge pots of water to the shrines as
part of the worship of the Hindu god Shiva.
   The accident occurred during the monsoon season, when the Ganges
reaches a width of one mile near Katihar.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
