<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Gulf     08-07 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Gulf,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: British Warship Nearly Downed Cargo Plane In Persian Gulf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A newspaper reported Sunday that a British warship
came within 10 seconds of shooting down a civilian aircraft over
the Persian Gulf last year.
   The weekly Observer, quoting unidentified air traffic
controllers in Dubai, United Arab Emirates, reported that the
destroyer HMS Cardiff last year targeted surface-to-air missiles at
a cargo plane.
   The Ministry of Defense said it would not comment on the report,
and the Observer reported no comment from the Royal Navy.
   The article follows an inquiry by the United States into the
July 3 downing by the guided-missile cruiser USS Vincennes of an
Iran Air jetliner. The United States said Navy forces mistook the
jetliner for an Iranian F-14 fighter. All 290 people on board the
jet were killed.
   In Sunday's report, the Observer did not specify the date or
further identify the cargo plane. It said the alleged incident
never had been disclosed.
   Air traffic controllers quoted by the newspaper said the
incident showed the dangers of foreign warships operating in the
gulf, where Iran and Iraq have both attacked shipping in their
8-year-old war.
   The Cardiff was on routine escort duty when the cargo plane flew
over the ship by mistake, and the pilot was not linked to an
emergency military radio frequency that could have been used to
warn him, the newspaper quoted the controllers as saying.
   When the pilot did not respond to warnings from the ship, the
Observer said, ``preparations were made to shoot down the plane.
Anti-aircraft missiles were within 10 seconds of being launched
when a final check revealed the plane was not hostile.''
   The air traffic controllers also said a U.S. Navy warship once
ordered a British Airways flight to change course and nearly caused
it to crash into another aircraft.
   In Washington, Maj. Alan Freithe, the Pentagon's weekend duty
officer, refused comment on the report.
   The Dubai air traffic controllers said they ``swiftly
countermanded'' the order from the U.S. Navy ship and avoided a
collision between the two planes, the Observer reported.
   A Pentagon report blamed the July 3 incident on human error by
radar operators without combat experience, who wrongly informed
Capt. Will C. Rogers III that the airliner appeared to be an
attacking fighter, Defense Department officials said. The report
also blamed the accident on stress under combat with Iranian
gunboats.
   In an April 18 skirmish with Iranian gunboats, confusing radar
signals caused three other American warships to believe they were
under attack by non-existent Iranian missiles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
