<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-88 1747EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-07 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Over Northeast And South, Hot On Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered over New England, the
South and the northern Plains on Sunday, and record high
temperatures returned to the upper Midwest.
   Tropical storm Alberto was northeast of Cape Cod, Mass., and was
expected to move near Nova Scotia sometime Monday. Highest
sustained wind speed was 40 mph, with higher gusts near squalls.
The storm produced heavy rain over parts of eastern Maine, but it
was expected to mostly affect marine interests off the coast of New
England.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered from central and
eastern New England south to the mid Atlantic Coast as a cold front
moved through New England.
   Low pressure over southeastern Louisiana scattered numerous
showers and thunderstorms along the central Gulf Coast into the
southern half of Alabama. Some storms produced locally heavy rain,
with 2.11 inches of rain in the 24 hours up to 7 a.m. at the New
Orleans Audubon zoo, with 2.05 inches at Thibodaux, La.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered over much of eastern
and southern Florida, and extended from eastern Georgia into
southeastern Tennessee and over southeast Missouri.
   Melbourne, Fla., got 1.99 inches of rain in the six hours up to
2 p.m.
   Showers and thunderstorms extended from northwestern and
north-central Minnesota into eastern South Dakota, developing along
a cold front that was pushing eastward into the upper Mississippi
Valley and southward into the central Plains.
   The cold front dragged cooler, drier air into the northern
Plains. Behind the front, northerly wind carried temperatures in
the 60s and 70s across the northern Rockies into the northern
Plains.
   Ahead of the front, temperatures were in the low to mid 90s from
southern Minnesota and southwestern Wisconsin into the middle
Mississippi Valley, and near 100 from the lower Missouri Valley
into the central and southern Plains.
   Record highs Sunday were 99 at Des Moines, Iowa; 96 at La
Crosse, Wis.; 100 at Sioux City, Iowa; and 107 at Waco, Texas.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55
degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 105 at Waco, Texas. The nation's low
Sunday morning was 34 at Truckee, Calif.
   For Monday, widespread showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from the upper Great Lakes through the lower Missouri Valley and
the central high Plains into the Colorado Rockies. Scattered
showers and thunderstorms were forecast from the southern Atlantic
Coast through the central Gulf Coast into Florida.
   Highs in the 70s were predicted along the Pacific Coast and
across northeastern North Dakota through northern Minnesota; in the
mid 90s to 105 from the middle and lower Rio Grande Valley of Texas
into the southern Plains; between 100 and 110 over the desert
Southwest; and in the 80s to low 90s across much of the rest of the
nation.
</TEXT>
