<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chile-President     08-07 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile-President,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Commander Says Presidential Candidate Should Run As
Civilian</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The commander of the national police said
in an interview published Sunday that the candidate in the
presidential referendum should run as a civilian and not as a
military officer.
   ``The new president is going to be a civilian,'' Gen. Rodolfo
Stange told the newspaper El Mercurio.
   He was asked if he meant that if the nominee is a military
officer he should retire from the armed forces and he replied
``Yes.''
   Gen. Augusto Pinochet, the army commander who has ruled Chile
since leading the bloody coup in September 1973 that ousted the
elected government of Marxist President Salvador Allende, is
expected to be the only nominee.
   Stange and the heads of the three military branches _ Pinochet,
navy commander Jose Merino and air force chief Fernando Matthei _
are scheduled to determine on Aug. 30 who the nominee will be.
Merino and Matthei also have publicly said the candidate should run
as a civilian.
   After the Aug. 30 nominating meeting the commanders will
announce a specific date for the referendum that is expected to be
held in early October.
   If a majority of voters approve of the nominee he will begin an
eight-year presidential term next March. If the nominee is rejected
by most voters an open election will be held in 1990, with Pinochet
remaining in office until then.
   Pinochet's central source of authority in nearly 15 years of
rule has been his command of the army, the largest and most
powerful military branch.
</TEXT>
