<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gulf-USNavy     08-07 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-US Navy,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New U.S. Warships Sent to Gulf Region as Replacements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. nuclear-powered aircraft carrier
and nine other warships steamed into the Arabian Sea to replace
other U.S. vessels in helping to protect Persian Gulf oil
shipments, the U.S. Navy said Sunday.
   However, the Navy said the changes were routine and unrelated to
diplomatic efforts to establish a truce in the 8-year-old Persian
Gulf war. They left the level of U.S. forces in the region
essentially unchanged, said a Navy official, who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
   The 91,487-ton carrier Carl M. Vinson and its battle group, all
based on the U.S. West Coast, replaced an East Coast contingent
headed by the carrier Forrestal. That group was in the region since
mid-May.
   The Navy has kept a carrier battle group in the Arabian Sea for
the past year to provide air support for the warships escorting
U.S.-flagged tankers inside the Persian Gulf. Pentagon officials
have said that the United States will reduce its 27-ship force in
the gulf region if and when a cease-fire in the war between Iran
and Iraq goes into effect.
   Arriving with the Carl M. Vinson were the nuclear-powered
cruiser Texas, the missile destroyers Robison and Goldsborough, the
frigate Fanning, the oilers Roanoke and Passumpsic, the ammunition
ship Flint and the Niagara Falls, a supply ship.
   The Forrestal and its escorts were en route back to the United
States. The group included the destroyer Spruance, missile
destroyers Dahlgren and Semmes, frigates Pharris and Elmer
Montgomery, the oiler Milwaukee and the ammunition ship Suribachi.
   The missile cruiser Vincennes, which pulled out of the gulf two
weeks ago, is continuing to operate in the Arabian Sea, military
officials said. The Vincennes shot down an Iranian commercial
airliner, killing all 290 people aboard, on July 3. The Navy said
the warship mistook the airliner for an Iranian F-14 fighter.
</TEXT>
