<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Governors 2ndLd-Writethru a0483 08-07 0786</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Governors, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0483,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governors Told States are `Center of Activism'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS top five grafs pvs to recast ld and edit for transition</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's governors agreed privately to
keep presidential politics from dominating their annual meeting, at
which President Reagan and Democratic presidential candidate
Michael Dukakis plan to make separate appearances, a source said
Sunday.
   Also Sunday, a White House official told the governors that
``state governments are now the center of activism.''
   Frank J. Donatelli, chief White House liaison to the governors,
said that President Reagan's goal throughout his presidency has
been ``diminishing federal intrusion into state affairs.''
   Before the start of the annual meeting of the National Governors
Association, Republican Gov. John Sununu of New Hampshire, NGA
chairman, and Democratic Gov. Gerald Baliles of Virginia, who will
be the next chairman, agreed the state executives ought to avoid
presidential politics.
   A source familiar with the discussions, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Sununu and Baliles then urged their fellow
governors to avoid discussion of the campaign.
   The governors were meeting between the national political
conventions that selected Dukakis, the governor of Massachusetts,
as the Democratic presidential nominee and that will designate Vice
President George Bush as the Republican candidate next week.
   Dukakis planned to attend the closing session of the NGA meeting
Tuesday and also meet with Democratic governors. Bush had no plans
to attend the meeting, but Reagan was flying to the session Monday
to address the governors.
   At a news conference opening the NGA meeting on Saturday,
Sununu, a strong backer of Bush and frequent critic of Dukakis,
steadfastly refused to talk about the campaign. He said he would
``display tremendous discipline'' in an effort to steer clear of
presidential politics.
   Despite the agreement to steer clear of partisan politics,
Republican Gov. Jim Thompson of Illinois described Dukakis' views
on foreign policy as ``naive at best.''
   Sununu and Thompson are among three governors mentioned as
potential choices for the GOP vice presidential nomination. The
other is Carroll Campbell of South Carolina.
   Donatelli said that as a result of Reagan's push to give more
responsibility to the states, ``state governments are now the
center of activism; they make things happen.''
   Donatelli said that ``through economic growth, block grants and
tax reform and especially regulatory reform, President Reagan has
persisted in his efforts to decentralize government.''
   There was bipartisan agreement that Reagan had won the fight
with the governors over transfer of domestic programs to the states.
   Gov. Richard Celeste of Ohio, a Democrat, noted that in the
early years of Reagan's presidency there was ``bipartisan
resistance'' to his proposals to shift responsibility for domestic
programs to the states.
   ``Yet, here we are, seven and one-half years later, not too far
from perhaps where the president first thought we ought to be,''
said Celeste, the host governor for the 80th annual meeting of the
NGA.
   The first formal sessions of the conference dealt with reports
on education and rural development.
   Gov. John Ashcroft of Missouri, chairman of the NGA subcommittee
on education, said his panel found ``an amazing number and variety
of initiatives'' launched in states to improve education.
   Cited were programs to improve teacher training and recruitment,
make greater use of communications technology, and provide health
and educational services to poor children.
   Iowa Gov. Terry Branstad, chairman of the Rural Development Task
Force, told a hearing, ``The time has come for a new national
commitment to revitalize rural America.''
   The report issued by the task force called for giving
communities greater say in the design of aid programs.
   Branstad said the farm economy had been improving but was now in
a new crisis because of the prolonged drought.
   ``The full impact of the drought in rural America remains to be
seen,'' said Branstad. He said the drought already had brought ``a
return of anxieties'' to many rural communities.
   The record federal budget deficits have been a dominant topic at
governors conferences throughout the Reagan presidency.
   ``At the very time that states governments have suffered
significant reductions in federal funds, the federal deficit itself
has increased,'' said Baliles.
   ``If the federal government doesn't have the money to spend, who
will carry out the functions that have traditionally been carried
on at the federal level?'' asked Baliles.
   He said it was essential to debate ``the nature of the power
relationship that exists between the different levels of
government.''
   Celeste said the shift of responsibility for many domestic
programs had not occurred in a systematic way ``but there is no
question, it seems to me, that we are, as state governments, in a
position where we have assumed a much larger responsibility.''
</TEXT>
