<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Politics     08-07 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Politics,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Rule Imposed After Gandhi Party Members Bolt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal authorities took control of a
northeastern state on Sunday, news agencies said, after defections
from Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's governing party threw the region
into a political crisis.
   The agencies also said the state legislature of Nagaland, a
region on the Chinese border that has seen years of tribal
rebellion, was dissolved.
   A federal official in New Delhi, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said that when 13 Nagaland legislators, including four
ministers, resigned from the Congress Party last week, they caused
``instability in a vital northeastern state which has a history of
insurgency.''
   Gandhi's Congress Party won 31 seats in the 60-member state
legislature in November elections. However, the defectors said the
state government had failed to live up to popular expectations and
joined efforts to form a new party.
   Their departure reduced the party to minority status.
   Tribal Naga rebels had demanded secession from India, but many
participated in the November elections.
   Federal rule will extend for six months to give time for new
legislative elections.
   Nagaland is the third Indian state to come under federal
control. The others are the northern state of Punjab, where radical
Sikhs are demanding a homeland, and politically unsettled Tamil
Nadu in the south.
