<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PuertoRico-Fraud     08-07 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Puerto Rico-Fraud,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Charged In Scheme To Sell Food From School Lunch Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two government employees were
charged Sunday with embezzling thousands of dollars from school
lunch programs by allegedly reporting food had spoiled and then
selling it to private firms.
   Justice Department officials said the charges, filed after a
two-year investigation, involve hundreds of thousands of dollars
worth of food that was marked as rotten and then sold to
wholesalers and stores instead of destroying it, the San Juan Star
reported.
   It said most of the food was surplus produce donated by the U.S.
Department of Agriculture, which gave $17 million worth of goods to
Puerto Rico's Education Department last year.
   Juan E. Berrios, director of the School Lunchroom Storage and
Distribution Service, was charged with seven counts of theft
involving more than $50,000 worth of sugar, canned fruit, rice,
corned beef, canned salmon, cereal, dehydrated potatoes and cheese.
   Olga Arroyo Medina, a Health Department inspector from the town
of Dorado, was charged with eight counts of failing her duties as a
public servant by not ensuring the food was destroyed after it had
been marked as unsuitable.
   That is a misdemeanor and she was not present as the charges
were presented at the Superior Court in the suburb of Bayamon.
   The charges against Berrios involve felonies and the judge set
his bail at $14,000. Berrios was released later Sunday after
posting bail.
   A preliminary hearing was set for Aug. 24.
   Although the food involved in the charges was from an Education
Department warehouse in Vega Alta, 10 miles west of San Juan,
officials said the same procedure was carried out at other
warehouses.
   Two other former government workers _ the Vega Alta warehouse
director and an employee _ were arrested on theft charges in
February and pleaded guilty.
   A wholesaler Berrios allegedly sold food to also was arrested
but was given immunity from prosecution after he agreed to turn
state's witness.
   Berrios, a native of the town of Cidra who faces felony charges,
was released after posting bail set at $14,000.
</TEXT>
