<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PennyMeters     08-07 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Penny Meters,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town to Replace Penny Parking Meters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELANIE BURNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOORESTOWN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The penny parking meters in this
affluent community are going the way of penny candy, and the
township's parking attendant says it's about time.
   ``Pennies are out,'' says Sylvia Davis, who has been the parking
violations officer for 15 years. ``You can't get anything with a
penny anymore.''
   The 162 penny meters, installed in the 1950s on seven streets in
the community of 15,700 near Philadelphia, will be replaced by
mid-August.
   Parking rates will rise from 1 cent to 5 cents for 12 minutes
and from a nickel to a quarter per hour.
   Beginning Monday, minimum parking fines will rise from $3 to $6.
   Mrs. Davis says she has spent a lot of time repairing the old
meters with her handy screwdriver.
   ``We can't get any parts for them,'' she says. ``They're
outdated.''
   The township agreed, and last month earmarked $34,200 to buy new
parking meters, says John M. Schoenberg, deputy township manager
and director of finance.
   Schoenberg said about a quarter of the old ones could no longer
be repaired. The township spent about $19,000 annually to maintain
them, but they only generated about $6,000, he said.
   The new meters will generate between $22,000 and $25,000 he said.
   Bill Phillips, production manager at Meter Products in Lodi,
N.J., estimated that three other towns in New Jersey and 10 in the
Northeast still have penny meters.
   Mrs. Davis, who issues about 40 meter violation tickets a day,
says the new meters will be easier to operate and drivers won't
have to scramble to find pennies.
   ``A lot of times, they can't find pennies,'' she said. ``A lot
of times they put dimes in and they don't take them.''
   Mrs. Davis says residents don't seem too upset by the meter
change.
   ``They're more interested about buying the (old) meters,'' she
says.
   Schoenberg says the township plans to sell the old ones to
residents and antique dealers, and that a working meter could go
for as much as $45.
   ``Everytime I talk to somebody the price gets a little higher,''
he says.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
