<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Violence, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0497,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Assailants Shoot Palestinian Village Leader in Stomach</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to CORRECT name of wounded village leader
in all references. Pickup 11th pvs, `Underground leaders ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assailants on Sunday shot and wounded the
traditional leader of an occupied West Bank Palestinian village, a
hospital official said. A Jewish settlement leader said the wounded
man collaborated with Israel.
   Mustafa Abu Bakr, 47, the village leader, or mukhtar, of Bidya,
was hit in the stomach four times and taken to Meir Hospital in
Kfar Saba, said the hospital's deputy director, Dr. Avinoam
Eliashiv.
   Bidya is 25 miles north of Jerusalem.
   Military sources said Abu Bakr was sitting outside his home with
his children when assailants opened fire from 15 yards away. One of
his sons was slightly wounded in the hand, said the sources,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Israel Television said Abu Bakr probably was shot by
Palestinians. Israel radio reported that the gunman fired a
Soviet-designed submachine gun.
   The army command said it was investigating the report.
   Ron Nahman, mayor of the nearby Jewish settlement of Ariel, said
Mustafa had collaborated with Israel.
   He also said it was the second attempt on Abu Bakr's life since
the Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule in the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip broke out eight months ago. According to U.N.
figures, 237 Palestinians and four Israelis have been killed in the
uprising.
   ``In April, Arabs tried to blow up his home along with his wife
and seven children,'' Nachman said in a telephone interview. ``They
put six gas balloons alongside the wall of his house and lit them.''
   Nachman said Abu Bakr fired at his assailants before Israeli
troops and Jews from nearby settlements rescued him.
   Underground leaders of the Palestinian uprising have issued
several leaflets calling for the assassination of Arabs who
continue to collaborate with Israel.
   On Feb. 24, Palestinians from the village of Qabatiye, near
Jenin, lynched an alleged collaborator.
   Two weeks later, a Palestinian policeman working for the
military government was stabbed to death in the Aqbat Jaber refugee
camp near Jericho.
   Other alleged Palestinian collaborators have been forced to flee
their villages because Israeli authorities have been unable to
guarantee their safety.
   Nachman warned that Palestinians might try to assassinate more
Arabs. ``As the army hedges them in, they will try to intimidate
Arab collaborators,'' said Nachman. ``It will get worse and there
will be more assassinations.''
</TEXT>
