<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-88 1939EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines-Aquino     08-07 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines-Aquino,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aquino Defends Relatives Against Allegations of Corruption</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino on Sunday
defended a brother-in-law who a newspaper said had gained control
of businesses seized by the Aquino government.
   She commented in her weekly radio program about allegations of
corruption in her administration and said, ``It is very clear to me
it is not really my relatives that they are hitting but me. They
want to erode my credibility.''
   She also denounced critics who have said her government is no
different from that of Ferdinand Marcos, deposed as president in
February 1986 in a civilian-military uprising that brought Mrs.
Aquino to power.
   ``I disagree very vehemently on this,'' she said. ``In the first
place, my predecessor engaged in wholesale graft and corruption. .
.. I challenge anybody to say that I have ill-gotten wealth.''
Marcos is living in exile in Hawaii.
   The Presidential Commission on Good Government has seized about
$300 million worth of assets that belonged to Marcos, his relatives
and associates. They have been accused by officials in Mrs.
Aquino's government of obtaining as much as $10 billion illegally
during Marcos' 20-year rule.
   Mrs. Aquino's comments Sunday were in response to a newspaper
report that her brother-in-law, Ricardo Lopa, had gained control of
36 companies seized by the government from Benjamin Romualdez, a
brother of Marcos's wife Imelda, shortly after Marcos was ousted.
   Mrs. Aquino said her family owned 60 percent of the companies in
question but the firms were taken over by Marcos's relatives when
he imposed martial law in 1972. The businesses include shipping and
construction companies.
   In her radio address Mrs. Aquino said that shortly after she
became president she lost interest in acquiring the shares her
family had owned in the companies but Lopa wanted to buy back the
15 percent his family owned.
   She said Lopa's proposal to buy back his shares is still being
studied by the Presidential Commission on Good Government.
   ``I think my relatives can get into business without receiving
any special privilege, and you know I have been very strict on
this,'' Mrs. Aquino said.
   It was the second time Mrs. Aguino has become involved in
allegations involving her relatives.
   Last year she ordered the National Bureau of Investigation to
investigate claims that a sister-in-law, Margarita Cojuangco, had
received $1 million from an Australian businessman in exchange for
a gambling concession.
   Mrs. Cojuangco denied the charge and eventually was cleared by
the bureau.
</TEXT>
