<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Anglicans     08-07 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Anglicans,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Episcopal Leader Calls for Progressive Anglican Churches</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANTERBURY, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of U.S. Episcopal Church
on Sunday told Anglican bishops split over whether to allow women
bishops not to let their churches ``be a museum of the past.''
   The issue of consecrating the Anglicans' first woman bishop gave
rise to bitter disputes and an inconclusive compromise at the
three-week conference of bishops representing 70 million Anglicans
worldwide.
   The move is expected within a few months by one of seven
churches, including the U.S. Episcopal, which have ordained 1,200
women priests.
   Bishop Edmond L. Browning, who leads 2.5 million U.S.
Episcopalians, spoke at a service in 800-year-old Canterbury
Cathedral. It capped the often stormy Lambeth Conference, the 12th
such gathering since Anglican bishops first met in 1867.
   Without making a direct reference to the controversy over women
bishops, Browning called on bishops to move away from ways of the
past. However, he combined his appeal with a call for unity.
   ``To have unity, to have authority, the Anglican Communion must
not be a museum of the past but the household of faith for the
future,'' he said.
   The conference debates ended with leaders of the 27
self-governing churches, representing Anglicans in 164 countries,
expressing determination to remain united.
   In a compromise on the issue, Archbishop of Canterbury Robert
Runcie, who led the conference, was instructed to set up and head a
new commission to examine how the churches will maintain unity
despite divisions over women bishops.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
