<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Television     08-07 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Television,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Government To Close Independent Broadcasting Authority</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British government plans to scrap the private
broadcasting authority that regulates the country's commercial
television, The Sunday Times of London reported.
   The newspaper said that a government policy review due in
November would recommend replacing the Independent Broadcasting
Authority with an agency that can take more advantage of the
consumer choice offered by satellite and cable television.
   Britain has four broadcast television channels, all based on a
tradition that use of the airwaves is a public service accountable
to the people through the national government in Parliament.
   Two national channels are operated by the British Broadcasting
Corp., which is publicly funded by fees that television users pay
annually for the privilege of owning a set.
   The authority, created in 1955, regulates the other two channels
which offer a mixture of national and regional programming funded
primarily by advertising sales.
   Government ministers have concluded that the authority engaged
in anti-competitive practices by forming an advertising cartel that
pushed up the price of television ads 37 percent in the past two
years, despite falling viewership compared to the BBC, the
newspaper said.
   The authority has also been criticized for failing to control
program standards, the newspaper said. Mrs. Thatcher has warned the
authority to curb what she calls excessive sex and violence on
television.
   A particular irritant, the newspaper said, has been Channel 4,
introduced in 1982 to give Britons a wider choice of local
programming. The Sunday Times said the government perceives a
left-wing bias in the channel's current affairs programs.
   The Sunday Times quoted Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, whose
Conservative Party government has promoted deregulation throughout
British industry, as calling the IBA ``the last bastion of
restrictive practices.''
   The authority's chairman, Lord Thomson, called the plan ``an act
of folly ... like throwing the baby out with the bathwater,'' the
newspaper said.
   Disbanding the authority would require the approval of
Parliament, where Mrs. Thatcher's party enjoys a 101-seat advantage
in the House of Commons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
