<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0453 08-07 0799</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0453,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says He'll Debate More Than Once</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with Dukakis campaign comment, INSERT two grafs
after 6th pvs, ``We can't...president said.''; pick up 7th pvs,
``Bush also...platform committee.''; EDITS 21st graf, ``Last
week...bipartisan panel,'' to delete Estrich first reference.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush said Sunday
he will agree to ``more than one'' debate with Democrat Michael
Dukakis, but isn't ready to pin himself down on how many, when or
where.
   ``I'm ready to commit to debates,'' Bush said after attending
church with his family at this seacoast resort where he has a
summer home.
   He denied an accusation by the Dukakis campaign that he was
shying away from confronting his Democratic rival.
   ``Not only do I want debates, but I have to because I've got to
get him to stand by his record,'' the vice president said.``We've
got to spell these differences out and debates are a good way to do
it.''
   In the debates, Bush said, he would hammer home his contention
that Dukakis is soft on defense.
   ``We can't risk the peace and national security of this country
on someone as unexperienced as the governor of Massachusetts,'' the
vice president said.
   Dukakis campaign manager Susan Estrich said, however, that Bush
``is talking tough to the cameras but is refusing to meet Mike
Dukakis in a face-to face-debate.''
   ``If George Bush wants to debate foreign policy, Mike Dukakis is
ready,'' she said. ``The vice president's resume didn't help him
when it mattered. He sat silently by while the administration
peddled arms to the Ayatollah.''
   Bush also said he would tell Republican platform drafters on
Monday in New Orleans to ``be a little more specific than the
Democratic platform committee.''
   Bush will be the leadoff speaker before the GOP panel.
   It was to be a one-day trip. Bush was to return to New Orleans,
where he will be installed as the GOP presidential nominee, on Aug.
16.
   ``I think the country is entitled to know the specifics,'' Bush
said. ``The govenor of Massachusetts says he is a liberal, says he
is a card-carrying member of the ACLU (the American Civil Liberties
Union), and that didn't come out of the convention.
   ``They masked it. They cramped down any discussion of individual
initiatives. Mine will be somewhat more specific.''
   The vice president attended church with 22 members of his
family, who occupied the first two pews of St. Ann's Episcopal
Church.
   With him were his wife, Barbara, his 87-year-old mother, Dorothy
Walker Bush, his five adult children and their spouses, and his ten
grandchildren.
   ``We try to get together once every summer,'' Bush said. ``This
is that weekend.''
   The vice president and his family spent much at his oceanfront
home taping television commercials for the fall campaign.
   Speaking with reporters, Bush said he was not worried about
recent polls showing him trailing Dukakis by 17 or more points.
   He blamed the gap on what he suggested was an artifical boost
Dukakis got from the Democratic convention. ``They've had their day
in sun,'' he said. ``Now we will have our day.''
   He said that he would continue to press Dukakis on issues.
``It's not negative (campaigning),'' Bush said. ``It has to be
done. And once it's done, the polls will take care of themselves.''
   He accused Dukakis of ``flip flopping'' on a freeze on nuclear
weapons, of mismanaging the budget of Massachusetts and of seeking
to ``cut the muscle out of our strategic defense.''
   And, said Bush, ``He goes down to New Jersey and talks about the
pollution off New Jersey and look, over his shoulder is Boston
harbor, one of the most seriously polluted bodies of water in this
country.''
   Last week, Estrich and Paul Brountas, Dukakis' campaign
chairman, sent a letter to Bush campaign officials criticizing the
vice president for not agreeing to a series of three presidential
debates and one vice presidential debate proposed by a bipartisan
panel.
   ``There will be debates. And I look forward to them,'' Bush
said. ``But I'm not the nominee of our party yet and we have plenty
of time to determine how many, where and all of that.''
   ``There'll be more than one debate, but how many...has not been
sorted out yet,'' he said.
   Appearing Sunday on NBC's ``Meet The Press,'' outgoing Treasury
secretary James A. Baker III, also declined to discuss how many
debates Bush would be willing to hold with Dukakis. Baker is
resigning to head Bush's campaign.
   Asked he he had made any progress in narrowing his list of
possible running mates, Bush said, ``not really.''
   However, he gave a flat ``no'' to one reporter's question on
whether he was considering a ticket in which President Reagan would
hold the No. 2 slot.
</TEXT>
