<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RaftingDeaths     08-07 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rafting Deaths,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Die In Raft Accident Filming Former Governor's Show</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLENNALLEN, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three people fell from a raft and died
while filming a television program with former Gov. Jay Hammond in
a rapid river in mountainous southeastern Alaska, authorities said.
   Hammond was one of the seven people aboard the 16-foot raft, but
he was not injured, said Vaughn Baker, a National Park Service
ranger at Glennallen.
   The accident occurred Saturday afternoon on the Tana River in
the Wrangell-St. Elias National Park and Preserve, about 240 miles
east of Anchorage.
   Four people were flipped out of the raft by rapids in the Tana
River Canyon, but a woman was pulled back aboard, Baker said.
   Two passengers were found unconscious, and could not be revived,
Baker said. The third victim was found dead early Sunday, he said.
   The victims were not immediately identified.
   Authorities were notified of the accident on Saturday, and the
survivors were rescued Sunday.
   Hammond retired from politics after serving as Alaska governor
from 1974 to 1982. Hammond and the others were filming a segment
for his program, ``Jay Hammond's Alaska,'' which features
interviews with Alaska residents.
   After the accident, guide Paul Claus and a passenger floated
downstream to a gravel bar that serves as a landing strip. Claus'
father, John, spotted an emergency signal on the landing strip when
the party failed to arrive at a scheduled pickup point, Baker said.
   Returning in a smaller plane, the elder Claus picked up his son
and flew to a ranger station about 20 miles east of the canyon. A
helicopter could not reach the canyon because of darkness, said
Baker.
   In the meantime, supplies were dropped to the survivors and
another guide hiked upstream to help the group overnight.
</TEXT>
