<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Opposition     08-07 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Opposition,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition Alliance Chooses Leader To Challenge Congress Party</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Front, a new alliance of
seven parties, on Sunday elected a movie actor as its chairman to
lead the fight against Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi and his Congress
Party.
   The National Front was formed Saturday to challenge the
governing Congress Party in national parliamentary elections
scheduled for the end of 1989.
   Under India's electoral system, the head of the party that wins
the most seats in Parliament becomes prime minister.
   The new chairman, N.T. Ramo Rao, told a news conference Sunday
that the seven parties in the front will retain their separate
identities but will field their candidates on a single slate.
   Rama Rao, known for portraying Hindu gods in his film roles,
heads the Telegu Desam party based in the southern state of Andhra
Pradesh.
   With 30 seats, his party is the largest opposition group in the
544-member Parliament. Gandhi's party has 415.
   The other parties in the National Front are Janata, Lok Dal, Jan
Morcha, Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam, Asom Gana Parishad and a
breakaway faction of the Congress Party.
   Former Defense Minister Vishwanath Pratap Singh, once an ally of
Ghandi and now a critic, was given the No. 2 job in the National
Front. Singh, who heads the Jan Morcha (Peoples' Front), won a
parliamentary seat in a by-election in June. He has said he does
not want to be considered for the prime minister's post.
</TEXT>
