<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-88 2035EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HospitalStrike     08-07 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hospital Strike,0417</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Settlement May Avert Strike at Two Hospitals; Other Strikes
Continue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tentative settlement was reached Sunday
in contract talks for 1,600 nurses at two city hospitals, but
strikes by nearly 4,000 nurses and other workers continued at eight
private hospitals.
   Nurses at San Francisco General Hospital, Laguna Honda Hospital,
and several city health clinics set a Monday strike deadline, but
extended it on a day-to-day basis.
   ``We reached this settlement on time because none of the parties
wanted to add to the health care fears that have permeated this
city'' since the labor disputes began, said Mayor Art Agnos at a
City Hall news conference.
   Details of the pact were not released. Local 790 of the United
Public Employees sought to reduce nurse-patient ratios and improve
measures to retain and recruit nurses. Pay was not an issue.
   Talks were held around-the-clock, and the settlement was reached
about 4:30 a.m. Sunday, said Eileen Mahoney, a spokeswoman for the
mayor's office.
   San Francisco General Hospital cares for the city's poorest and
sickest patients and Laguna Honda has about 1,000 elderly patients.
   Union members will vote on the proposal Tuesday.
   Agnos also called for an immediate resumption of bargaining in
the strikes, adding he planned to ``very actively, very
aggressively'' involve himself and other city officials in the
disputes.
   No new talks have been scheduled in the strikes.
   Seven hospitals were struck July 26 by 1,700 licensed vocational
nurses and hospital workers represented by Local 250 of the
Hospital and Health Care Workers Union. On Aug. 2, more than 2,000
registered nurses represented by the California Nurses Association
struck at six of those facilities.
   On Saturday, 130 nurses represented by the California Nurses
Association and an undetermined number of service workers
represented by Local 250 also went on strike at French Hospital.
   The struck hospitals have remained open.
   The strike by Local 250 is mainly over health benefits and sick
leave. Increased pay is the issue with the California Nurses
Association, which wants an 11 percent raise for the first year and
a 10 percent raise the second year of a two-year contract.
   The hospitals are negotiating as a group called Affiliated
Hospitals, and have offered 18 percent raises over 31 months, which
would cost the affected six hospitals $40 million.
   Talks with French Hospital employees are separate from the other
negotiations.
</TEXT>
