<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Sihanouk-Thatcher     08-07 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sihanouk-Thatcher,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sihanouk Meets Thatcher; Says Cambodia's U.N. Seat Should Be
Declared Vacant</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos BK1, BK4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOLLY YONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SITE B, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Norodom Sihanouk said Sunday that
Cambodia's seat at the United Nations should be declared vacant
because the Khmer Rouge is exploiting it to try to improve its
blood-stained image.
   Sihanouk spoke with reporters at Site B after escorting British
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher on a tour of the camp, which holds
53,000 refugess. Site B, 5{ miles from the Cambodian border, is the
main civilian base for Sihanouk's followers.
   Mrs. Thatcher was on the second day of a visit to Thailand and
is to return to London Tuesday.
   She presented some of the refugees with cooking utensils, yarn,
English-language textbooks, cloth and medicine. Britain has given
more than $20 million in aid to the refugees and will provide
another million dollars this year, she said.
   Mrs. Thatcher said she agreed with Sihanouk that the Khmer Rouge
should not be allowed to return to power.
   Sihanouk's supporters are in a fractious alliance with the
radical Khmer Rouge and anti-communuist forces waging guerrilla
warfare against the Vietnamese-installed Cambodian government.
   Sihanouk was deposed and the Cambodian monarchy abolished in
1970. The Khmer Rouge gained power in the spring of 1975, defeating
the U.S.-backed government, and hundreds of thousands of Cambodians
were killed in a brutal campaign to establish a communist agrarian
society.
   In December 1978 the Vietnamese invaded Cambodia, ousted the
Khmer Rouge and installed another communist government.
   Cambodia's U.N. seat remained with the Khmer Rouge, but its
delegation was joined by representatives of the two other
resistance groups after the three formed an alliance in 1982.
   Sihanouk said that declaring the Cambodian seat vacant would
help efforts to find a settlement to the war.
   Representatives of the Vietnamese and Cambodian governments met
for the first time with leaders of the resistance groups last month
in Indonesia, but no significant progress was reported. Vietnam has
an estimated 100,000 soldiers in Cambodia.
   Sihanouk resigned in July as president of the resistance
coalition, saying Khmer Rouge guerrillas were attacking his
supporters. ``More than 100 officers and soldiers died in such
recent attacks,'' he said Sunday.
   He also said opposition to the Khmer Rouge had led not only to a
truce but even to cooperation between his forces and the Cambodian
government.
   ``It is a question of survival,'' he said.
   Mrs. Thatcher told a gathering of thousands of refugees:
   ``The Vietnamese must go. But we must not allow the return of
the murderous Pol Pot regime to return. No civilized country could
accept that.''
   Pol Pot was the head of the Khmer Rouge during its bloody
1975-78 purges, but he was removed from positions of power after
the Vietnamese ousted his government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
