<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Eighty-Eight 2ndLd-Writethru a0500 08-07 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eighty-Eight, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0500,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town on Brink of Philatelic Immortality</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 10th graf `ABC's `Good' to add more specific location
for town.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES WOLFE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EIGHTY EIGHT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This normally placid little farm town
busted loose Sunday in anticipation of a once-in-a-lifetime
celebration _ the magic day of 8-8-88 in Eighty Eight.
   A swarm of visitors brought bumper-to-bumper traffic to the
town's only thoroughfare for Sunday's festivities, which included a
parade, antique car show and the cutting of a commemorative cake _
8 feet, 8 inches long; 8.8 inches wide and 8.8 inches high.
   But the most talked-about part of the town's celebration was set
for Monday night: the marriage of Tom Accardo and Deborah Muhlbeier
of Casper, Wyo., at 8:08 p.m. That's 8:08 on 8-8-88 in Eighty Eight.
   The couple had not yet set a date when they learned of the town
on a television news report.
   ``Deb just looked at me and said, `Wouldn't that be fun to go in
there and get married on 8-8-88 in Eighty Eight, Kentucky?''' said
Accardo, 29, a sales representative for a supply company.
   The couple tried to write the mayor of Eighty Eight, soon
learning there wasn't one, Accardo said. They heard instead from
postmistress Donnie Sue Bacon, and plans for an outdoor wedding,
performed by a county magistrate, soon took shape.
   Pearl Russie of DeKalb, Ill., was among Sunday's early arrivals,
driving up to the front steps of the Eighty Eight Market in her
Oldsmobile Delta 88. Her license plate, ``ANY 88,'' was an
immediate attention-grabber.
   ``I'm an 88 freak,'' said Ms. Russie, 45, a custodian at
Northern Illinois University.
   She had to buy a new set of tires to make the 500-mile trip,
but, ``when I heard there was a town called Eighty Eight, I had to
come here,'' she said.
   ABC's ``Good Morning, America'' on Monday planned to broadcast
from the town in south-central Kentucky farm country about 40 miles
east of Bowling Green.
   ``It's fun. We won't ever have this happen again,'' said Mrs.
Bacon, who this year became the darling of stamp collectors around
the world.
   Mail has been arriving in bundles at the tiny post office from
collectors covetous of Mrs. Bacon's Eighty Eight postmark.
   Postal Service regional headquarters in Louisville sent a mobile
post office to help with postmarking and to hawk a variety of
philatelic items.
   They included specially embossed envelopes and postcards, plus
stamp collector kits. The most popular goodies, however, were royal
blue caps, T-shirts and sun visors with a facsimile Eighty Eight,
Ky., postmark.
   Across the street at the market, owner Rosemary McPherson sold
her own shirts and caps.
   Ms. Russie bought four T-shirts and 20 postcards. She also took
advantage of the market's commemorative menu.
   ``I got a special 88-cent hamburger,'' she said. ``Four cents
tax makes 92, so there's 8 cents change. Good.''
   Legend has it that Eighty Eight was named by Dabnie Nunnally, a
postmaster in the 1860s. He wanted to give the town a digital name,
reached into his pocket, found 88 cents in change, and that was it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
