<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HearinKidnapping     08-07 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hearin Kidnapping,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hearin Pleads With Kidnappers To Release His Wife</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto JX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX DOMINGUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wealthy businessman made a public plea
Sunday for the release of his wife, who was apparently kidnapped
from the couple's home nearly two weeks ago.
   Annie Laurie Hearin, 72, disappeared July 26, and her husband,
Robert Hearin, found a ransom note at their home that evening.
Authorities have said the vaguely worded note suggests the
kidnapping may have been an act of vengeance stemming from Hearin's
business dealings.
   ``Like any businessman, I have made decisions which may appear
to others as unfeeling, but those appearances are not true,'' said
Hearin, reading from a statement outside his home. ``Moreover,
those business decisions were mine, not my wife's, and she had
nothing to do with them.
   ``My children and I appeal to whomever has my wife to return her
safely to us,'' he said, with his daughter and son standing behind
him.
   Hearin is president of the Mississippi Valley Gas Co., and has
insurance and bank holdings. His worth is estimated at $100 million.
   Mrs. Hearin was last seen by a family maid after a bridge game.
She suffers from an intestinal disease that doctors say could be
fatal if she does not receive daily medication.
   The ransom note instructed Hearin to pay an unspecified amount
within 10 days to former employees of School Pictures of
Mississippi Inc., of which Hearin is a major stockholder.
   The note named 12 men whom authorities identified as disgruntled
former employees of the company, which takes pictures of school
children.
   The 10-day deadline expired Saturday without further word from
the kidnapper or kidnappers on the amount or method of payment.
   After making the statement, Hearin did not answer questions, and
Mayor Dale Danks, who was at his side, would not talk about details
of the case.
   ``Mr. Hearin felt, obviously, that he wanted to communicate. As
you know he has been waiting for some time for additional
instruction,'' Danks said. ``He made it very clear at the outset
that the initial contact and the only contact that had been made
was very vague for him to understand and carry out.''
   Danks would not say whether Hearin has attempted to make
payments to any of the 12 named in the note.
</TEXT>
