<HEAD>Heat Wave Kills 38 In Central China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A heat wave has killed 38 people in the central
Chinese city of Wuhan, an official report appearing Sunday said.
   The China News Service, in a dispatch published in Hong Kong
newspapers, said the heat wave that began last month was the worst
in 39 years.
   It said temperatures in Wuhan reached 104 degrees on some days.
The report did not elaborate.
   Wuhan is on the Yangtze River, 630 miles south of Beijing.
   In July, the Chinese press reported the heat wave killed 71
people in Shanghai, 290 in the southern city of Nanchang and 83 in
the coastal city of Nanjing.
