<DOCNO> AP880807-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-88 2238EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CraterLake     08-07 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crater Lake,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientists Say Dives Exciting, But No Hot Springs Found Yet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARNARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CRATER LAKE NATIONAL PARK, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists on Sunday said
their first dive to the bottom of the nation's deepest lake was
exciting, but they didn't find any evidence of the thermal springs
they were seeking.
   Jack Dymond and Robert Collier, oceanographers at Oregon State
University, each used a one-person submarine to search Crater Lake
for hot springs that may be the remnants of the volcanic activity
that formed the lake nearly 7,000 years ago.
   ``We haven't found any actual thermal springs,'' said Dymond,
who Friday became the first man to reach the bottom of the lake.
``In some ways we're just getting started. I think in the next week
or 10 days we'll be much further along.''
   The oceanographers are taking part in a National Park Service
research project to determine why the lake is so clear. Visibility
in the lake has been measured to a depth of between 85 and 115 feet.
   The study was started after scientists in the 1970s noticed a
significant reduction in the clarity of the lake. Recent
measurments have shown the clarity returning to levels last
measured in the 1930s.
   The deepest point in the lake is 1,932 feet, making it the
seventh-deepest lake in the world. The lake is in southwestern
Oregon.
   Collier, who made his first dive Saturday, said it took about 20
minutes to reach the bottom and, at a depth of 1,200 feet, blue
light was still visible from above.
   Dymond likened the bottom to a moonscape, with 2-foot diameter
boulders and rock walls and ridges. He said he also saw what he
interpreted to be evidence of old hot springs _ deposits of iron
and manganese and rock formations with colored stains on holes or
cracks.
   While the submarine operated well, sonar echos off unexpectedly
craggy features on the bottom of the lake made precise navigation
difficult and efforts are being made to correct the problem, the
scientists said.
   ``We can only tell where we are every five minutes,'' Collier
said. ``I'd like to know every minute.''
   Precise navigation is important. Last year, while using a
remote-controlled submersible equipped with a video camera, the
scientists stumbled across what looked like a vent oozing a milky
substance. However, they never were able to relocate it to take a
temperature reading or a fluid sample.
   Crater Lake was formed after rain and melted snow filled the
basin left by the collapse of Mount Mazama in the Cascade Range
nearly 7,000 year ago.
   Both Dymond and Collier said they experienced brief moments of
fear during their descent, but quickly became engrossed in their
work.
   Collier said much of what he saw was sediment covering the
bottom, with wavy markings that may have been worm tubes. He said
he also saw small rocks and sunken pieces of trees that were
probably rafted out to the interior of the lake by ice as well as
an angular object apparently made by man that could have been
dropped off a tour boat.
   ``I pretty much saw the same thing for five hours,'' Collier
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
