<DOCNO> AP880807-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-88 2327EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Belgium-USMissiles     08-07 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Belgium-US Missiles,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Inspectors to Visit U.S. Missile Base in Belgium</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of Soviet inspectors will check
a base for U.S. cruise missiles and a maintenance plant this week
in Belgium, the U.S. Embassy announced Sunday.
   The inspectors will visit the facilities under terms of the
Intermediate Nuclear Forces Treaty, signed by the United States and
Soviet Union in December. The agreement eliminated an entire class
of weapons with a range of 600-3,000 miles.
   The Soviet inspectors will arrive in Belgium on Monday and visit
the cruise missile base in Florennes, site of the 485th U.S.
Tactical Missile Wing, on Tuesday, the embassy said. The base is
about 50 miles southeast of Brussels.
   During the tour, they will also inspect the SABCA aviation plant
in nearby Gosselies, where the missiles are maintained, the embassy
said. It did not say how many inspectors would be in the group.
   Sixteen cruise missiles were deployed at Florennes in 1985.
Another 32 missiles were to be deployed if the treaty had not been
signed.
   Cruise missiles are ground-hugging missiles that can elude radar
detection.
   Similar Soviet inspections have already taken place in West
Germany, Britain, Holland and Italy, as well as in U.S. test
plants. U.S. inspectors are also inspecting facilities in East bloc
nations under the treaty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
