<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0641 08-07 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0641,0543</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: AMs separate moved on Wright as a0673, on Devereux as a0617</NOTE>
<BYLINE>J. Skelly Wright</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Retired federal Judge J. Skelly Wright, who
handled the Pentagon Papers case and wrote the decree ending de
facto segregation in the nation's capital, died Friday of cancer.
He was 77.
   He retired last year after 25 years on the U.S. Court of Appeals
here _ two as chief judge _ and 13 years as a U.S. District Judge
in his native New Orleans, where he began public service as
assistant U.S. attorney in 1937.
   After his 1960 order desegregating the New Orleans school system
drew threats against his life, he was reassigned to Washington,
D.C., where he overturned the school system's racially separate
``tracking system'' in 1967.
   In the Pentagon Papers case of 1971, Wright's minority opinion
that The New York Times and Washington Post had the right to
publish the secret documents on the Vietnam War was upheld by the
U.S. Supreme Court on a 6-3 vote.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>James Devereux</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James P.S. Devereux, a World War II hero and
former congressman, died Friday of pneumonia. He was 85.
   He earned the Navy Cross leading the Marines' defense of Wake
Island during a Japanese attack in 1941. Devereux, who spent the
rest of the war in Japanese prison camps, was elevated to brigadier
general at his retirement in 1948.
   He was elected to Congress as a Republican in 1950, representing
Maryland's 2nd District. He gave up his seat eight years later to
run unsuccessfully for governor against J. Millard Tawes.
   In 1960, he was named Republican chairman for the district and
was Baltimore County director of public safety from 1962 to 1966.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Joseph Caruso</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEBAGO, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jopseph A. Caruso, founder and chairman of
the board of Bar Harbor Airways, died Friday. He was 67.
   Caruso, a native of Lawrence, Mass., founded the airline with
his brother Thomas in 1946 with three airplanes operating from the
town pier in Bar Harbor. The airline expanded rapidly in the early
1970's, and has become one of the nation's largest commuter lines.
Selling a half-interest to Texas Air in 1986, the company changed
its name to Eastern Express.
   Caruso subsequently founded Maine Aviation Corp. in Portland.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>George Templar</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Templar, a retired U.S. district
judge and former member of the Kansas Legislature, died Friday. He
was 83.
   He practiced law after graduating from Washburn University at
Topeka in 1927 and in 1933 was elected to the state House, serving
until 1941. He was elected to the Kansas Senate in 1944 and served
for several terms.
   In 1953, President Eisenhower appointed him U.S. attorney for
Kansas. The following year he resigned to run for the Republican
nomination for governor. He lost to Fred Hall, who became governor.
   Templar was named to the federal bench in 1962 and retired in
1974.
   Among his cases were the appeals of Perry Smith and Richard
Hickock, who were executed for the 1959 murders of four members of
the Clutter family. The case was chronicled in the book ``In Cold
Blood'' by Truman Capote.
</TEXT>
