<DOCNO> AP880807-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-07-88 0132EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MistrialJudge     08-07 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mistrial Judge,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DA's Office to Review Judge's Mistrial Declaration to Attend
Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The District Attorney's office has ordered an
internal review of a Superior Court judge who declared a mistrial
in a drug case when it conflicted with a convention he planned to
attend, officials said.
   Judge Stephen Lachs, 48, said attorneys assured him the trial
would end Aug. 3, a day before he was to leave for an American Bar
Association convention in Toronto, where he was to preside over a
meeting of the family courts committee.
   Lachs, appointed to the court in 1979, said from Toronto on
Friday he hoped the defendant could be tried again, but said both
the prosecutor and the defense attorney knew of his time constraint.
   ``I had my plans to be at the ABA ... annual meeting, and that
was it,'' Lachs said.
   But Chief Deputy District Attorney Gilbert I. Garcetti claimed
the defendant will be set free because the mistrial was declared
before the jury ruled on her guilt or innocence.
   The internal review could lead to a request by the District
Attorney's office for an investigation by the state Commission on
Judicial Performance, which evaluates allegations of impropriety
and makes recommendations to the state Supreme Court.
   A criminal defendant cannot be tried twice for the same offense
and such constitutional protection takes effect as soon as a jury
is sworn in.
   The only exceptions are when one of the lawyers, the judge or
the defendant becomes ill, or when there is a hung jury. In such
cases, a new trial is generally scheduled.
   The jury in the case before Lachs was sworn in Tuesday and ready
to hear final arguments Wednesday afternoon in a trial for felony
possession of about one gram of rock cocaine.
   When a postponment date to accommodate the judge's schedule
couldn't be agreed upon by the attorneys and jurors involved, Lachs
declared a mistrial.
   ``I couldn't think of any other option _ other than to cancel my
flight, which I could have done. I admit that,'' the judge said.
</TEXT>
