<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Iran-Oil     08-07 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Oil,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Says It Is Determined To Help Achieve OPEC Unity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said Sunday it was determined to
play its part in achieving unity among members of the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries, Tehran radio reported.
   The radio report, monitored by British Broadcasting Corp., said
Oil Minister Golamreza Agazadeh made the comment during a meeting
with a delegation of officials from Oman.
   ``The achievement of a sincere unity in the decisions taken by
OPEC requires great effort and cooperation by all the members,''
Agazadeh was quoted as saying.
   ``We are determined to play our role in achieving this goal,''
he said.
   Some OPEC leaders have expressed hope that a cease-fire in the
Iran-Iraq war could help boost oil prices.
   During the war, Iran has been discounting its oil and Iraq has
been producing far more than under its last official OPEC output
quota. In addition, disagreement by the two war enemies over how
large a quota the other should have has worsened attempts by the
fractious cartel to reach consensus on how best to raise oil prices.
   The theory is that if the war ends, Iran and Iraq will be more
disciplined.
   The world oil cartel has been attempting to raise the average
price of crude to $18 per 42-gallon barrel. Recently, world prices
have been at least $1 to $2 below that level.
</TEXT>
